## Cluster Setup (for testing)

This project was tested on a local kind cluster with cert-manager and metrics-server installed:

```bash
# Create cluster
kind create cluster --name k8s-1.34 --image kindest/node:v1.34.3

# Install cert-manager
kubectl apply -f https://github.com/cert-manager/cert-manager/releases/download/v1.14.0/cert-manager.yaml

# Install metrics-server
kubectl apply -f https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/metrics-server/releases/latest/download/components.yaml
```

---

## Why This Approach?

Production Kubernetes upgrades are risky. A wrong upgrade can:
- Remove APIs your workloads depend on → immediate outage
- Break admission webhooks → block all deployments cluster-wide
- Introduce CRD incompatibilities → operators stop reconciling silently

Existing tools (Pluto, kubent) only check deprecated APIs. This tool goes further by combining live cluster inspection with LLM reasoning to surface operator compatibility issues, failure scenarios, and a structured remediation plan — the kind of analysis a Senior Platform Engineer would perform before any production upgrade.

